  "text": "## Health Check Endpoint Implementation Comparison\n\n### Kubernetes (kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\nKubernetes implements a comprehensive health checking system across three endpoints: `/healthz`, `/livez`, and `/readyz`.\n\n**Files:**\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz.go` - Main health endpoint registration and handler logic\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go` - Core health check framework and built-in checkers\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/config.go` - Configuration and registry initialization\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/options/etcd.go` - etcd health and readiness checks registration\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/storagebackend/factory/factory.go` - Storage factory for creating health checks\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/storagebackend/factory/etcd3.go` - etcd3-specific health check implementation\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/storage/etcd3/healthcheck.go` - etcd3 health check implementation\n\n**Key Features:**\n- Default checks: `PingHealthz` (always succeeds) and `LogHealthz` (verifies logging is not blocked)\n- Three distinct endpoints with different semantics:\n  - `/healthz` - Basic liveness check (backward compatibility)\n  - `/livez` - Liveness probe (can have a grace period before boot completes)\n  - `/readyz` - Readiness probe (no grace period, must pass before serving traffic)\n- **Dependencies checked:**\n  - **etcd**: Separate health and readiness checks created via `CreateHealthCheck()` and `CreateReadyCheck()` in the storage factory\n  - **Informers/Cache sync**: `NewInformerSyncHealthz` checks if shared informers have synced\n  - **Shutdown state**: `NewShutdownHealthz` marks readiness as failed during graceful shutdown\n  - **Post-start hooks**: Wraps hooks to fail livez until completion\n  - **Logging**: `LogHealthz` monitors if klog is blocked\n- Health checks can be added dynamically via `AddHealthChecks()`, `AddReadyzChecks()`, and `AddLivezChecks()`\n- Supports grace periods for livez checks, allowing time for startup before expecting liveness\n- Individual checks can be excluded via query parameters\n- Supports grouped checks for category-based inclusion/exclusion\n\n### Grafana (grafana/grafana)\n\nGrafana implements health checking with two main endpoints: `/healthz` and `/api/health`.\n\n**Files:**\n- `pkg/server/health.go` - Health notifier for managing readiness state\n- `pkg/api/health.go` - Database health check logic\n- `pkg/api/http_server.go` - HTTP server setup and health handler registration\n\n**Key Features:**\n- `/healthz` - Simple liveness endpoint that always returns 200 OK if the web server is running (no actual checks)\n- `/api/health` - Full health endpoint that checks both liveness and database connectivity\n- **Dependencies checked:**\n  - **Database**: Queries the database with `SELECT 1` to verify connectivity\n  - **Cache**: Health check result is cached for 5 seconds to avoid excessive database queries\n  - **Version info**: Returns build version, commit, and enterprise commit (if not hidden)\n- Returns 200 OK if database is accessible, 503 Service Unavailable if database check fails\n- Uses `HealthNotifier` type to manage readiness state (separate from livez probe)\n- Implements `LivezHandler()` and `ReadyzHandler()` for pod probe endpoints via `RegisterHealthEndpoints()`\n- Simple implementation focused on database connectivity as the critical dependency\n\n### Prometheus (prometheus/prometheus)\n\nPrometheus implements health checking with two endpoints: `/-/healthy` and `/-/ready` (non-standard paths compared to Kubernetes conventions).\n\n**Files:**\n- `web/web.go` - HTTP server setup and probe endpoint handlers\n\n**Key Features:**\n- `/-/healthy` - Liveness probe that always returns 200 OK with message \"[AppName] is Healthy.\" (purely alive, not dependent on readiness)\n- `/-/ready` - Readiness probe that checks if the server has completed initialization\n- **Dependencies checked:**\n  - **Ready status flag**: Uses atomic `ready` flag that must be explicitly set to `Ready` by the main process\n  - **Stopping state**: Returns 503 with `X-Prometheus-Stopping: true` header when shutting down gracefully\n  - **Initialization**: Returns 503 during startup until `SetReady(Ready)` is called\n- Simple state-based approach: the `testReady()` wrapper function checks the `ready` status flag\n- No built-in checks for storage, cache, or external dependencies; entirely based on manual status management\n- The `SetReady()` function also updates a Prometheus gauge metric `readyStatus` (1 for ready, 0 for not ready)\n- Supports HEAD requests on both endpoints for minimal overhead\n\n## Summary of Differences\n\n**Kubernetes:** Most comprehensive with pluggable health check framework, multiple endpoints with different semantics, grace period support, and extensive dependency checks (etcd, informers, logging, shutdown state).\n\n**Grafana:** Moderate approach with two endpoints, primary focus on database connectivity, simple caching strategy for health status.\n\n**Prometheus:** Minimal approach with state-based readiness, no built-in dependency checks, relies on explicit application-level state management, uses non-standard endpoint paths."
}
